{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512032"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11833"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11833"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.54,0.07,0.15,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78090"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4434"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63512"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"6426"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26801"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78090"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with pain in his right flank for the past week. The nature of the pain is sharp and colicky and each episode lasts for 20 minutes, with nausea and vomiting associated with the pain. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he looks slightly dehydrated, with dry mucous membrane and decreased skin turgor. His observations show respiratory rate 18/min, pulse rate 88/min, blood pressure 130/80mmHg, and temperature 37.2C. There is tenderness in his right flank.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn urinalysis, blood is present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Based on the clinical picture, which one of the following site is the most likely site of pathology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Renal pelvis","Ureteropelvic junction","Ureteral crossing of the iliac vessels","Ureterovesical junction","Bladder"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENephrolithiasis is a common condition that occurs more in males than females. Its peak incidence is 45-70 years. Risk factors include personal/ family history, low fluid intake, dehydration, loop diuretics and post colectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen nephrolithiasis occurs, patients often present with severe unilateral colicky flank pain (renal colic) that radiates to the lower abdomen, groin, labia, testicles or perineum. It usually worsens progressively and pain is often associated with nausea, vomiting and haematuria. The pain typically waxes and wanes in severity and develops in waves or paroxysms. Paroxysms of severe pain usually last 20 to 60 minutes. Pain is thought to occur primarily from urinary obstruction with distention of the kidney capsule. Consequently, pain due to a kidney stone typically resolves quickly after passage of the stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpper ureteral or kidney pelvic obstruction will usually lead to flank pain or tenderness, whereas lower ureteral obstruction causes pain that may radiate to the ipsilateral testicle or labium. The location of the pain may change as the stone migrates. Flank pain can occur from hydronephrosis, which could result from a stone impacted at any site along the ureter. Thus the site of the pain will not necessarily reflect the precise site of a stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the patient has had persistent flank pain which has not moved in site for one week. That, together with the finding of flank tenderness, is very suggestive that the stone is lodged high in the urinary tract - and from the options provided, the most likely site of obstruction is at the pelvic-ureteric junction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal stones usually get lodged in the narrowest parts of the urological system. There are three narrowing at the ureter, where kidney stones typically become lodged:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe ureteropelvic junction (UPJ)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe ureteral crossing of the iliac vessels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe ureterovesical junction (UVJ)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, in this case, with flank pain, the most likely site of stone impaction will be the \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteropelvic junction.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The 3 sites where kidney stones typically become lodged are: The ureteropelvic junction (UPJ), the ureteral crossing of the iliac vessels, and the ureterovesical junction (UVJ).","Flank pain and haematuria are classic symptoms of renal colic, often indicating a kidney stone."],"references":["Ordon M;Schuler TD;Ghiculete D;Pace KT;Honey RJ; M. Stones Lodge at three sites of anatomic narrowing in the ureter: Clinical fact or fiction? [Internet]. Journal of endourology. U.S. National Library of Medicine; [cited 2022Jun16]. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22984899/","UpToDate [Internet]. Uptodate.com. 2022 [cited 24 July 2022]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/kidney-stones-in-adults-diagnosis-and-acute-management-of-suspected-nephrolithiasis?search=renal%20stones\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H3717995259","Sewell J, Katz DJ, Shoshany O, Love C. Urolithiasis - Ten things every general practitioner should know. Aust Fam Physician. 2017 Sep;46(9):648-652. PMID: 28892595. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28892595/","Khan SR, Pearle MS, Robertson WG, Gambaro G, Canales BK, Doizi S, Traxer O, Tiselius HG. Kidney stones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Feb 25;2:16008. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.8. PMID: 27188687; PMCID: PMC5685519. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27188687/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63512"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T13:29:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T13:30:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4434"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78090"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,